What is Repository Pattern
The idea of RP is to abstract our database implementation (F.g DAL pattern) by defining the interaction with it to the interface.
This means the RP should be free of any implementation details.
A good example is when we want to have multiple database implementations and switch between them.

Keeping Business Logic away from your database (data center)

This concept is very important, because by doing this we can completely separate our logic code with the database code and connect them through an abstraction layer like interfaces.
For example, imagine this source base:
we have a software that will add score to the users each time a user press the â€˜scoreâ€™ button. by doing that we have 2 separate titles here:

add score
save it to the database

for doing that in a way that we can have â€˜Repo Patternâ€™, we can do something like this: (golang)

type application struct {
	users       User
	store       Store
}

// Sample of using Store and user that are separated in implementation
func (app* application) addScore(user *User) {
	var user = app.store.getUser(_username)

	user.appendScore()

	app.store.updateUser(_username, user.score)
}

type User struct {
	username string
	family   string
	score    int
}

func (user *User) appendScore(amount int) error {
	user.score += amount
	return nil
}

//  This is the important abstraction layer part
// Any type that implements these functions can
// be a Store.
type Store interface {
	getUser(username string) *User
	updateUser(username string, new_score int)
}

// A sample type that implements Store interface
type PostgresStore struct {
	db *DB

	user *User
}

func (p* PostgressStore) getUser(user *User) *User {
	// find the user
}

func (p* PostgressStore) updateUser(user *User) *User {
	// update the user
}


